# Part 2 – K3s with three applications and Ingress

This part deploys three web applications on a single K3s node and exposes them using an Ingress controller (Traefik). The routing is based on the Host header:

Hostname      | Destination application | Replicas
app1.com      | app1 (nginx)            | 1
app2.com      | app2 (nginx)            | 3
any other     | app3 (nginx)            | 1

The entire environment runs inside a single Vagrant VM (yourloginS). Alpine Linux is used, with K3s version 1.27.12 – the last version fully compatible with cgroup v1.

## Requirements

- Same as Part 1 (VirtualBox, Vagrant)
- Internet connection (to download the base box, K3s, and container images)

## Directory structure

p2/
├── Vagrantfile
├── confs/
│   └── config.env
└── scripts/
    ├── setup-k3s.sh      # installs K3s server (v1.27.12) on Alpine
    └── deploy-apps.sh    # creates deployments, services, and Ingress

## Configuration

Edit confs/config.env:

LOGIN="your42login"
OS_BOX="generic/alpine318"
CPU_COUNT=1
RAM_MB=1024
SERVER_IP="192.168.56.110"
NETWORK_INTERFACE="eth1"

Note: This part uses K3s v1.27.12 to avoid cgroup v2 requirements on Alpine. Do not attempt to upgrade to v1.28+ without enabling cgroup v2 first.

## Deploying the environment

cd p2
vagrant up

The provisioning will:
1. Launch the Alpine VM with hostname yourloginS
2. Install K3s server (v1.27.12) with Traefik enabled (default)
3. Deploy the three nginx deployments and corresponding Services
4. Create an Ingress resource that routes traffic based on Host
5. Wait for all pods and Traefik to become ready

## Verification

1. Check Kubernetes resources:

vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get nodes"
vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get pods"
vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get ingress"

2. Test Ingress routing:

vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "curl -H 'Host: app1.com' http://192.168.56.110"
vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "curl -H 'Host: app2.com' http://192.168.56.110"
vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "curl -H 'Host: anything.com' http://192.168.56.110"

All should return the default nginx welcome page.

3. Verify replica count for app2:

vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get pods | grep app2 | wc -l"
# Should output 3

## Troubleshooting

- API not ready: The provisioning script waits up to 120 attempts (2 seconds each) for the API to respond. First-run image pulls may take longer – increase the loop count if needed.
- Ingress not working: Ensure Traefik is running (kubectl get pods -n kube-system). The default K3s installation includes Traefik; do not add --disable=traefik.
- Cgroup errors: If you see "kubelet is configured to not run on a host using cgroup v1", you have installed a K3s version >=1.28. Downgrade to v1.27.12 as shown in setup-k3s.sh.

## Clean up

vagrant destroy -f

## Note on cgroup v2

Alpine Linux uses cgroup v1 by default. K3s versions 1.28 and above require cgroup v2. This project deliberately uses K3s 1.27.12 to remain compatible with Alpine out-of-the-box. If you wish to use a newer K3s, you must first enable cgroup v2 on Alpine (kernel parameters, rc_cgroup_mode="unified", and a reboot).

## What is demonstrated

- Single-node K3s cluster on Alpine
- Deployment of multiple applications with different replica counts
- Kubernetes Services (ClusterIP)
- Ingress routing (Traefik) based on virtual hosts
- Full automation with Vagrant and shell provisioning
